item.title: Putin Rival Alexei Navalny in Critical Condition After Suspected Poisoning
item.description: Russian opposition politician Alexei Navalny, a critic of President Vladimir Putin and Moscow’s political elite, was admitted to an intensive-care unit after a suspected poisoning left him unconscious, his spokeswoman said.

item.title: Inside the Rise of Mohammed bin Salman
item.description: The Saudi crown prince ascended with a taste for opulence, a hunger for money and a drive for power.

item.title: Battered Eurozone Could See More Stimulus in the Fall
item.description: European Central Bank officials signaled that they could roll out new monetary stimulus to shore up economic growth.

item.title: Turkey Keeps Rates Unchanged Even as Lira Plumbs Record Lows
item.description: The Turkish central bank kept its benchmark interest rate unchanged, in line with President Recep Tayyip Erdogan’s demand to keep it low, but leaving the emerging economy exposed to further capital flight and a potential currency crisis similar to the selloff that beset Turkey two years ago.

item.title: Covid-19 Hits India's Already Faltering Consumers Hardest
item.description: India’s emerging middle-class consumers, until a few years ago the engine of the world’s fastest-growing big economy, were faltering even before the coronavirus arrived. The pandemic has all but knocked them out.

item.title: How China Targets Scientists via Network of Recruiting Stations
item.description: China is targeting top scientific and technological expertise in the U.S. and other advanced nations through an expanding network of more than 600 talent-recruitment stations around the world, a new report has found.
